2026-04-16 12:18:15 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module 3'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that with all switches ON and a good 12 V supply, the output of control module 1 provides a normal +12 V / 0 V pair, and control module 2 also provides a normal +12 V / 0 V pair. However, from control module 3 onward (modules 3 to 8, and the load input) both conductors are at 0 V relative to the supply reference. That means the fault that removes the 12 V rail from the series chain appears first at control module 3.\n\nSince module 2 is confirmed to output a valid +12 V, either:\n- the 12 V conductor from module 2 is not actually connected to the correct 12 V input terminal of module 3, or\n- control module 3 internally fails to pass the 12 V through from its input to its output (e.g., an open or mis‑wired trace), despite its switch being ON.\n\nBecause prior cabling inspection could not resolve pin‑to‑pin details, the most consistent single root cause within the given component list is an internal fault or misconnection in Control module 3 that prevents the +12 V line from propagating further, leaving all downstream modules and the load with only 0 V on both lines.'
